{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"70bceae0-9a1d-46ad-85a4-78e5877d7888","content":"The project isn't in the current directory, but here's the standard `mcp.json` configuration for a C# stdio MCP server in VS Code:\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — most C# MCP servers use stdio transport (via `WithStdioServerTransport()` or similar).\n- **`dotnet run`** builds and runs the project. For a published binary, replace with the path to the executable.\n- If your server uses **SSE** transport instead, use `type: \"sse\"` with a `url` field pointing to the endpoint.\n- Add `\"env\": { \"KEY\": \"value\" }` if your server needs environment variables.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1bdade4d-5413-4fd1-96f3-c4a67ad615ae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't actually exist. The user said they built it, but it's not in the current directory. Let me just give them the configuration guidance based on common C# MCP server patterns.","outputTokens":325},"id":"5e9c6dd8-b139-466c-865d-c94c2e5c1356","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:03:02.523Z","parentId":"2df513ef-8eea-4067-8873-3605ba667059"}
